
00:00:00,467 --> 00:00:01,869
The sharks are back

00:00:01,869 --> 00:00:03,737
in an all-new season
of "Shark Tank,"

00:00:03,737 --> 00:00:07,567
where hopeful entrepreneurs
from across the country

00:00:07,567 --> 00:00:10,200
dream of a chance
to secure an investment

00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:11,801
and gain powerful partners

00:00:11,801 --> 00:00:15,433
to start, grow, or save
their businesses.

00:00:15,433 --> 00:00:17,302
I decided to revolutionize
the dessert industry.

00:00:17,302 --> 00:00:20,038
(all) We can save lives,
and you can make money.

00:00:20,038 --> 00:00:22,040
If the sharks hear
a great idea,

00:00:22,040 --> 00:00:24,109
they're ready to invest
using their own money...

00:00:24,109 --> 00:00:26,845
I'll give you $1 million.

00:00:26,845 --> 00:00:29,647
And they'll fight each other
for a piece of the action.

00:00:29,647 --> 00:00:31,116
Listen to what he just said!

00:00:31,116 --> 00:00:31,450
(Robert)
Kevin, why would they--

00:00:31,450 --> 00:00:32,650
It doesn't matter
what you think.

00:00:32,650 --> 00:00:34,384
I couldn't care less.
It's what they think.

00:00:34,384 --> 00:00:37,187
But first the entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:37,187 --> 00:00:40,190
to invest the full amount
they're asking for

00:00:40,190 --> 00:00:42,192
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:42,192 --> 00:00:43,994
How can you come in here
and say,

00:00:43,994 --> 00:00:45,395
"I need to get clear
on the numbers"?

00:00:45,395 --> 00:00:46,730
I thought I had a good,
basic understanding of it.

00:00:46,730 --> 00:00:48,665
No, you were terrible.
It's sink...

00:00:48,665 --> 00:00:51,335
all I see is problems.
Or swim.

00:00:51,335 --> 00:00:52,669
We have an order from

00:00:52,669 --> 00:00:54,004
a very high-ranking
government official.

00:00:54,004 --> 00:00:55,472
How about president Obama?
Wow.

00:00:55,472 --> 00:00:56,740
♪♪

00:00:56,740 --> 00:00:59,943
Who are the sharks?

00:00:59,943 --> 00:01:03,680
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:03,680 --> 00:01:05,282
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:07,117 --> 00:01:09,453
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:09,453 --> 00:01:13,256
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:13,256 --> 00:01:17,794
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:17,794 --> 00:01:19,796
Barbara Corcoran
went from working

00:01:19,796 --> 00:01:20,731
as a waitress in Manhattan

00:01:20,731 --> 00:01:24,201
to building the city's
preeminent real estate empire.

00:01:24,201 --> 00:01:27,404
Daymond John is a fashion mogul
and branding expert

00:01:27,404 --> 00:01:30,674
who grew
his homemade clothing line

00:01:30,674 --> 00:01:33,610
into the globally recognized
fashion brand Fubu.

00:01:33,610 --> 00:01:36,546
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:36,546 --> 00:01:38,615
is now a technology mogul

00:01:38,615 --> 00:01:40,450
who sold his first
internet companies

00:01:40,450 --> 00:01:44,454
for over $350 million.

00:01:44,454 --> 00:01:46,256
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:46,256 --> 00:01:48,325
notorious
billionaire entrepreneur

00:01:48,325 --> 00:01:51,061
and the outspoken owner
of the Dallas Mavericks.

00:02:00,404 --> 00:02:04,133
♪♪

00:02:04,133 --> 00:02:05,468
First up is Carmen Lindner,

00:02:05,468 --> 00:02:10,339
selling a delicious new twist
on an old camping favorite.

00:02:17,046 --> 00:02:20,182
Hi.
My name is Carmen Lindner,

00:02:20,182 --> 00:02:22,985
and I am the founder and c.E.O.
Of gotta have s'more.

00:02:22,985 --> 00:02:25,788
I'm here seeking an investment
of $75,000

00:02:25,788 --> 00:02:29,258
in exchange for 25% equity
in my company.

00:02:29,258 --> 00:02:31,060
Quick show of hands here.

00:02:31,060 --> 00:02:32,128
Who likes s'mores?

00:02:32,128 --> 00:02:33,729
Me, too.

00:02:33,729 --> 00:02:35,731
But you know what I don't like?

00:02:35,731 --> 00:02:37,400
Camping.

00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:40,202
(sharks laugh)
So I decided to set out

00:02:40,202 --> 00:02:41,804
and revolutionize
the dessert industry.

00:02:41,804 --> 00:02:45,408
I want to introduce you
to the s'muffin.

00:02:45,408 --> 00:02:48,511
The s'muffin is a s'more
in the shape of a mini muffin.

00:02:48,511 --> 00:02:52,515
And I promise you have never
seen or tasted

00:02:52,515 --> 00:02:53,582
anything
quite like this before.

00:02:53,582 --> 00:02:54,984
You don't have to take
my word for it,

00:02:54,984 --> 00:02:57,920
'cause you get to try some
right now.

00:02:57,920 --> 00:02:59,388
Barbara, I want you
to remember something.

00:02:59,388 --> 00:03:01,324
A moment on the lips,
a lifetime on the hips.

00:03:01,324 --> 00:03:02,925
(Carmen) Oh.
(laughs)

00:03:02,925 --> 00:03:03,726
Thank you.

00:03:03,726 --> 00:03:05,528
You're welcome.

00:03:05,528 --> 00:03:06,862
They sure look yummy, huh?

00:03:06,862 --> 00:03:08,197
They are yummy.
Mmm.

00:03:08,197 --> 00:03:09,932
So the middle one
is dark chocolate.

00:03:09,932 --> 00:03:13,002
There's one that's chocolate
with caramel.

00:03:13,002 --> 00:03:14,937
And another half that is...

00:03:14,937 --> 00:03:16,272
thank you.

00:03:16,272 --> 00:03:17,606
(Carmen) Milk chocolate.

00:03:17,606 --> 00:03:19,475
Oh, that's a good one.

00:03:19,475 --> 00:03:20,943
(Kevin) Carmen, it's gotta be
a million calories.

00:03:20,943 --> 00:03:22,712
It's not
a million calories.

00:03:22,712 --> 00:03:23,713
It's only 200 calories,

00:03:23,713 --> 00:03:27,450
but I'm not trying
to market these as a fat-free.

00:03:27,450 --> 00:03:29,985
And so now that you've tried
your very first s'muffin,

00:03:29,985 --> 00:03:33,255
you know why my customers
are constantly coming back,

00:03:33,255 --> 00:03:37,460
saying, "Carmen,
I gotta have s'more."

00:03:37,460 --> 00:03:38,277
(Robert chuckles)

00:03:38,277 --> 00:03:40,043
Okay, Carmen, what--
what are your sales?

00:03:40,043 --> 00:03:43,780
My sales to date,
for two and a half year,

00:03:43,780 --> 00:03:44,915
are $250,000.

00:03:44,915 --> 00:03:47,050
And that's just within
local mark--L.A. market.

00:03:47,050 --> 00:03:49,586
What do you think
you're gonna do this year?

00:03:49,586 --> 00:03:53,457
This year, my forecast
is to do $165,000.

00:03:53,457 --> 00:03:54,758
How do you sell them,
Carmen?

00:03:54,758 --> 00:03:58,629
75% of my customers
come direct to me online

00:03:58,629 --> 00:04:00,631
or they phone in.

00:04:00,631 --> 00:04:01,965
That's been my primary focus
over the first two years.

00:04:01,965 --> 00:04:04,768
Do any stores
carry them as well?

00:04:04,768 --> 00:04:06,370
So there are a few stores
that carry 'em--

00:04:06,370 --> 00:04:09,239
Local specialty bakeries,
wine stores.

00:04:09,239 --> 00:04:09,973
(Mark)
How much do you sell it for

00:04:09,973 --> 00:04:11,375
and what does it
cost you to make?

00:04:11,375 --> 00:04:13,176
Costs me to make--

00:04:13,176 --> 00:04:14,845
$9.34 a dozen.

00:04:14,845 --> 00:04:17,648
I charge $29.95 a dozen.

00:04:17,648 --> 00:04:20,050
We deliver
throughout Los Angeles.

00:04:20,050 --> 00:04:22,719
And just recently, I was able to
launch the national shipping.

00:04:22,719 --> 00:04:25,122
These are the boxes
that I ship 'em in.

00:04:25,122 --> 00:04:26,423
So--
(Barbara)
You ship them frozen?

00:04:26,423 --> 00:04:28,158
Ship them frozen.

00:04:28,158 --> 00:04:29,426
5 pounds of dry ice
with a cooler.

00:04:29,426 --> 00:04:30,761
How much
is that cost for shipping?

00:04:30,761 --> 00:04:33,363
Shipping cost alone
is $54.

00:04:33,363 --> 00:04:34,698
Whoa.
That's a lot.

00:04:34,698 --> 00:04:36,299
Which is high, but...

00:04:36,299 --> 00:04:39,369
stop the madness, Carmen.
Let's walk through this.

00:04:39,369 --> 00:04:42,773
You've got a dozen little
shmuffins or shmores in there.

00:04:42,773 --> 00:04:45,442
And I have to pay 60 bucks
to get them...

00:04:45,442 --> 00:04:47,310
(laughs)
To my honey bunny in New York.

00:04:47,310 --> 00:04:48,645
All right?
Mm-hmm.

00:04:48,645 --> 00:04:50,113
That is, like, 10 bucks
a shmore.

00:04:50,113 --> 00:04:52,115
That's right in line
with all my comp--

00:04:52,115 --> 00:04:53,650
All my competitors.

00:04:53,650 --> 00:04:55,986
Is there anything else
out in the market

00:04:55,986 --> 00:04:57,320
comparable to this?

00:04:57,320 --> 00:05:00,390
No. This is my baby.

00:05:00,390 --> 00:05:01,758
I trademarked
the name "S'muffin."

00:05:01,758 --> 00:05:03,760
I didn't want to just
call it a s'more

00:05:03,760 --> 00:05:06,229
because honestly, it's so much
more than a s'more.

00:05:06,229 --> 00:05:08,765
It's a shmuffin.

00:05:08,765 --> 00:05:09,833
It's a s'muffin.
I get it,

00:05:09,833 --> 00:05:11,368
but the cost
is freaking me out.

00:05:11,368 --> 00:05:14,200
I'm just thinking--
What--what do you think
is expensive?

00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:15,935
It's 10 bucks a shmuffer.

00:05:15,935 --> 00:05:16,869
(Daymond laughs)

00:05:16,869 --> 00:05:19,272
My target market--
They're high-end customers.

00:05:19,272 --> 00:05:21,540
They're used to paying
shipping...
(Robert) But why argue
with you, Carmen?

00:05:21,540 --> 00:05:22,875
And I'm getting--
You're doing it today. You're
selling them at that price.

00:05:22,875 --> 00:05:24,277
Yeah, and--
Not that many.

00:05:24,277 --> 00:05:25,544
You haven't sold many shmuffers
at that price.

00:05:25,544 --> 00:05:27,667
She sells $165,000 a year.

00:05:27,667 --> 00:05:29,536
Are you selling
a lot of product

00:05:29,536 --> 00:05:31,538
that costs $60 a box?

00:05:31,538 --> 00:05:32,472
Come on.
Yes.

00:05:32,472 --> 00:05:34,574
That's crazy.
$50--

00:05:34,574 --> 00:05:36,776
Am I the only person
Who says that's insane?

00:05:36,776 --> 00:05:38,245
(laughs)

00:05:38,245 --> 00:05:39,579
I mean, you fedex this
across the country...

00:05:39,579 --> 00:05:41,581
you wouldn't bel--
Or you send your children
to college.

00:05:41,581 --> 00:05:42,916
(Mark and Daymond laugh)
You choose one.

00:05:42,916 --> 00:05:44,918
You wouldn't--
Like, think about that.

00:05:44,918 --> 00:05:45,719
You wouldn't believe

00:05:45,719 --> 00:05:47,787
the frenzy
that these things create.

00:05:47,787 --> 00:05:51,858
This is
the next dessert craze.

00:05:51,858 --> 00:05:53,393
All right, Carmen. I'm not
gonna invest in your shmagels.

00:05:53,393 --> 00:05:56,329
I'm out.

00:05:56,329 --> 00:05:58,865
(laughs) Sorry, Carmen.

00:05:58,865 --> 00:06:00,400
What's your background?

00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:03,536
I was an advertising
sales executive.

00:06:03,536 --> 00:06:05,538
I was laid off
during the recession.

00:06:05,538 --> 00:06:06,206
I got a severance package.

00:06:06,206 --> 00:06:09,042
My husband and I
had always dreamed

00:06:09,042 --> 00:06:12,646
of starting a s'more store,
and--

00:06:12,646 --> 00:06:13,647
What?

00:06:13,647 --> 00:06:15,048
I-I never met somebody Who
loves s'mores more than you.

00:06:15,048 --> 00:06:17,183
(laughs)
When you say "s'more,"

00:06:17,183 --> 00:06:18,451
it brings back
happy memories,

00:06:18,451 --> 00:06:20,387
and people
automatically smile.

00:06:20,387 --> 00:06:23,123
I see this all the time
at events.

00:06:23,123 --> 00:06:24,791
They're like, "Oh, my gosh.
These are unique.

00:06:24,791 --> 00:06:25,592
What is this, a cupcake?"

00:06:25,592 --> 00:06:27,327
I'm like, "Oh, no.
It's better than a cupcake.

00:06:27,327 --> 00:06:28,862
It's a s'muffin."

00:06:28,862 --> 00:06:31,464
And then they taste it,
and then just fall over.

00:06:31,464 --> 00:06:34,868
Then they order it
and go bankrupt.
(Daymond laughing)

00:06:34,868 --> 00:06:35,268
They come back.

00:06:35,268 --> 00:06:37,604
They come back
and they order over and over.

00:06:37,604 --> 00:06:41,274
My biggest cost
was investing

00:06:41,274 --> 00:06:44,311
in getting
the national shipping down.

00:06:44,311 --> 00:06:45,979
Why didn't you just
stay local then?
Yeah, like why are you--

00:06:45,979 --> 00:06:47,314
if it was gonna cost you
all your money--

00:06:47,314 --> 00:06:48,648
'cause I don't want
to stay local.

00:06:48,648 --> 00:06:50,450
I want everybody to be able
to have these.

00:06:50,450 --> 00:06:51,718
I want s'muffins
and gotta have s'mores...

00:06:51,718 --> 00:06:53,386
that's completely
different, though, than--
to be a national name.

00:06:53,386 --> 00:06:55,722
That's a whole different thing
than trying to make money.

00:06:55,722 --> 00:06:57,857
You have a huge market
in Los Angeles.

00:06:57,857 --> 00:06:58,191
Mm-hmm.

00:06:58,191 --> 00:06:59,659
And you've got
willing customers.

00:06:59,659 --> 00:07:01,795
Why focus on
trying to solve a problem

00:07:01,795 --> 00:07:02,529
that's not really
a problem?

00:07:02,529 --> 00:07:04,931
This was one focus.
(chuckles)

00:07:04,931 --> 00:07:06,800
I'm also now wanting
to start focusing

00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:07,400
on wholesaling as well.
(laughs)

00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:11,004
Carmen, you're so in love
with your s'muffins,

00:07:11,004 --> 00:07:13,606
you can't see the dollars
from the marshmallows.

00:07:13,606 --> 00:07:15,575
I'm out.

00:07:15,575 --> 00:07:17,310
(Robert) Carmen,

00:07:17,310 --> 00:07:19,446
you put yourself in a position

00:07:19,446 --> 00:07:21,781
where you have to ask for
$75,000 from us

00:07:21,781 --> 00:07:26,720
and give up 25% equity
to fix a problem

00:07:26,720 --> 00:07:28,788
that isn't generating
any sales.

00:07:28,788 --> 00:07:31,057
All I see is problems.

00:07:31,057 --> 00:07:34,861
I see it as building
my distribution.

00:07:34,861 --> 00:07:36,196
The s'muffins were good.
I'm out.

00:07:38,198 --> 00:07:41,668
Your strategy is, uh,
s'muffin crazy.

00:07:41,668 --> 00:07:44,738
So, um, I'm out.

00:07:44,738 --> 00:07:48,108
I like nothing more
than a real s'more.

00:07:48,108 --> 00:07:50,777
But when I tasted this,

00:07:50,777 --> 00:07:52,245
it didn't taste anything
really like it.

00:07:52,245 --> 00:07:55,849
So I'm going out just because
I don't like the muffin.

00:07:55,849 --> 00:07:58,385
And I feel badly
telling you that.

00:07:58,385 --> 00:07:59,986
Okay.
Okay?

00:07:59,986 --> 00:08:01,921
But good luck to you.

00:08:01,921 --> 00:08:03,390
Thank you.

00:08:03,390 --> 00:08:05,525
(Carmen) It was just weird

00:08:05,525 --> 00:08:09,195
that they didn't
go bananas over them.

00:08:09,195 --> 00:08:12,132
It's almost like I was
in the twilight zone... (laughs)

00:08:12,132 --> 00:08:16,336
Because that was--That's not
the typical reaction.

00:08:16,336 --> 00:08:19,472
How can there only be
a dozen of them in that box?

00:08:19,472 --> 00:08:20,740
'cause it's full of ice.

00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:23,643
You're shipping water
across the country.
(sharks laugh)

