00:10:08,186 --> 00:10:10,522
we both started working
in our parents' shop.

00:10:10,522 --> 00:10:11,656
The restaurant business
is in our blood.

00:10:11,656 --> 00:10:13,725
It's in our veins.

00:10:13,725 --> 00:10:15,193
It's just what we know.

00:10:15,193 --> 00:10:16,528
What can I get for you,
sir?

00:10:16,528 --> 00:10:16,862
I'd love to have
that slammin' Salmon.

00:10:16,862 --> 00:10:18,263
Slammin' Salmon?
You got it.

00:10:18,263 --> 00:10:19,664
Together, we've created
a sushi experience

00:10:19,664 --> 00:10:22,000
that's never
been done before.

00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:23,468
Can you add cucumber
to that?

00:10:23,468 --> 00:10:25,470
The artichoke.
Can I get that with crab?

00:10:25,470 --> 00:10:27,539
We've allowed the customer
to become the chef.

00:10:27,539 --> 00:10:29,341
So our customers
get to choose everything--

00:10:29,341 --> 00:10:30,876
From the type of wrap
they want to use

00:10:30,876 --> 00:10:32,010
to the rice
they want to use,

00:10:32,010 --> 00:10:34,379
the veggies, the proteins,
the sauces, the toppings.

00:10:34,379 --> 00:10:37,048
And nobody is doing
what we're doing today.

00:10:37,048 --> 00:10:38,717
Getting an investment
from the sharks is critical

00:10:38,717 --> 00:10:41,253
at this stage
of where we are as a company.

00:10:41,253 --> 00:10:42,654
I believe our business model
is gonna be the next great thing

00:10:42,654 --> 00:10:45,390
in ethnic food.

00:10:45,390 --> 00:10:46,057
And with
the sharks' investments,

00:10:46,057 --> 00:10:49,795
we're gonna be able
to explode this concept.

00:10:49,795 --> 00:10:52,798
♪♪

00:11:06,478 --> 00:11:07,412
Hello, sharks.

00:11:07,412 --> 00:11:09,700
My name is Yuen Yung.

00:11:09,700 --> 00:11:12,236
And I'm his younger brother
Peter Yung.

00:11:12,236 --> 00:11:13,905
Our business is
how do you roll?

00:11:13,905 --> 00:11:16,774
We are seeking $1 million

00:11:16,774 --> 00:11:18,442
for 12% of our company.

00:11:18,442 --> 00:11:20,978
How do you roll? Is
a fast-Casual restaurant

00:11:20,978 --> 00:11:22,780
where you can get sushi rolls
made to order,

00:11:22,780 --> 00:11:24,782
just the way you like it.

00:11:24,782 --> 00:11:26,450
Before we
came onto the scene,

00:11:26,450 --> 00:11:27,118
if you wanted sushi,

00:11:27,118 --> 00:11:29,187
you really
only had two choices.

00:11:29,187 --> 00:11:31,255
Option number one
was to go to

00:11:31,255 --> 00:11:33,124
a fancy, sit-Down
sushi restaurant

00:11:33,124 --> 00:11:35,193
where you had to dress right,

00:11:35,193 --> 00:11:37,061
you had to smell right,

00:11:37,061 --> 00:11:38,062
you gotta like techno music.
(laughing)

00:11:38,062 --> 00:11:40,264
And, you know,
those can be fun occasionally,

00:11:40,264 --> 00:11:41,199
if you want to spend more money
than you actually have

00:11:41,199 --> 00:11:43,367
trying to impress people
you really don't like.

00:11:43,367 --> 00:11:45,236
(chuckles)
So that leaves you
with your second option.

00:11:45,236 --> 00:11:46,971
You go down to
the local grocery store,

00:11:46,971 --> 00:11:50,041
you get a premade roll
made fresh "daily."

00:11:50,041 --> 00:11:52,844
You just don't know which day of
the week it was actually made.

00:11:52,844 --> 00:11:54,312
The quality is just subpar.

00:11:54,312 --> 00:11:57,048
And because of
Yuen's horrible experience,

00:11:57,048 --> 00:11:59,450
we started the sushi revolution
three years ago

00:11:59,450 --> 00:12:00,852
with just one location
in Austin, Texas.

00:12:00,852 --> 00:12:03,521
We've taken
the same food quality

00:12:03,521 --> 00:12:04,188
you get
at a high-end restaurant

00:12:04,188 --> 00:12:04,700
and paired it up

00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:06,902
with the convenience
of the grocery store.

00:12:06,902 --> 00:12:09,038
Unpretentious, good food
in a fast-casual environment.

00:12:09,038 --> 00:12:11,774
(Yuen) So we want you to
experience this for yourself.

00:12:11,774 --> 00:12:13,442
So, Barbara, we would like
to actually invite you up...

00:12:13,442 --> 00:12:14,777
how nice is this?

00:12:14,777 --> 00:12:16,545
So you can create
your own sushi roll.

00:12:16,545 --> 00:12:17,413
All right, Barbara, whenever
you go to how do you roll?

00:12:17,413 --> 00:12:19,481
Uh, the first thing
you want to do...

00:12:19,481 --> 00:12:19,882
Mm-hmm.
Is pick out
what kind of wrap you'd like.

00:12:19,882 --> 00:12:21,550
We have seaweed wrap,
and we have soy wrap.

00:12:21,550 --> 00:12:22,885
I'll take the soy wrap.

00:12:22,885 --> 00:12:23,819
Soy wrap. Good choice.

00:12:23,819 --> 00:12:25,821
And what you get to do
is pick out your protein.
Mm-hmm.

00:12:25,821 --> 00:12:28,023
We have crab stick,
chicken, salmon, tuna.

00:12:28,023 --> 00:12:29,691
I'll take the tuna.

00:12:29,691 --> 00:12:31,627
Okay, and we also have
proprietary sauces.
Wow.

00:12:31,627 --> 00:12:32,628
Okay, do you like
spicy, sweet?

00:12:32,628 --> 00:12:34,830
A little spicy.
A little spicy.

00:12:34,830 --> 00:12:35,964
Our best seller
is the spicy mayo.

00:12:35,964 --> 00:12:37,833
I'll take it.
And I'll go ahead
and put that on there.

00:12:37,833 --> 00:12:39,168
(Peter) You can have a seat,

00:12:39,168 --> 00:12:39,835
and I'll bring that
right out to you.

00:12:39,835 --> 00:12:41,904
Sharks, do not fear,
we have food for you, too.

00:12:41,904 --> 00:12:44,306
You're gonna get to sample
our other side of the menu,

00:12:44,306 --> 00:12:44,907
which is our featured rolls.

00:12:44,907 --> 00:12:46,241
He's making it right there.

00:12:46,241 --> 00:12:47,776
He's making it
right now.

00:12:50,679 --> 00:12:51,013
Thank you, Yuen.

00:12:51,013 --> 00:12:53,348
You bet.

00:12:53,348 --> 00:12:54,149
Daymond.

00:12:54,149 --> 00:12:55,484
Thank you.
Enjoy.

00:12:55,484 --> 00:12:57,419
Mmm.

00:12:57,419 --> 00:12:58,353
Thank you, sir.
There you go.

00:12:58,353 --> 00:12:59,621
Good sushi.
(mouth full) Fantastic.

00:12:59,621 --> 00:13:00,956
(Yuen) Thank you.
Thank you.

00:13:00,956 --> 00:13:02,291
Hurry. Hurry.

00:13:02,291 --> 00:13:03,625
Barbara, this is
your custom roll.

00:13:03,625 --> 00:13:04,426
There you go.
How nice is this?

00:13:04,426 --> 00:13:06,028
Yeah.
Mmm.

00:13:07,362 --> 00:13:09,164
(Daymond) Very good.
This is very good.

00:13:09,164 --> 00:13:11,300
So here's our question--

00:13:11,300 --> 00:13:13,569
Who wants to roll
with us?

00:13:13,569 --> 00:13:14,103
Yuen, how did you
get started in this?

00:13:14,103 --> 00:13:15,571
You know, it's funny.

00:13:15,571 --> 00:13:16,905
We both grew up
in the restaurant business.

00:13:16,905 --> 00:13:18,774
I actually said,

00:13:18,774 --> 00:13:19,108
"I'm never gonna be in
the restaurant business again.

00:13:19,108 --> 00:13:21,043
I'm never gonna work
with family,"

00:13:21,043 --> 00:13:21,944
'cause I had to work with
my parents growing up. (laughs)

00:13:21,944 --> 00:13:24,480
Uh, 14 years later,

00:13:24,480 --> 00:13:25,814
uh, here I am, standing
next to my brother.

00:13:25,814 --> 00:13:29,485
Tell us about the economics
of the business.
Absolutely.

00:13:29,485 --> 00:13:31,687
Uh, so we started franchising
two and a half years ago.

00:13:31,687 --> 00:13:33,021
We have sold 40 total.

00:13:33,021 --> 00:13:34,890
We've gotten
15 of them opened,

00:13:34,890 --> 00:13:36,225
two of them
are corporate stores.

00:13:36,225 --> 00:13:37,426
So the first two stores
are our own.

00:13:37,426 --> 00:13:39,094
We opened the first two.

00:13:39,094 --> 00:13:41,630
Since then, we've been
focusing on franchising.

00:13:41,630 --> 00:13:43,699
Got it.
And the franchisees--

00:13:43,699 --> 00:13:44,967
How long has
the longest one been open?

00:13:44,967 --> 00:13:48,237
Uh, one has been open
for right at about a year.

00:13:48,237 --> 00:13:49,438
And how are they doing?

00:13:49,438 --> 00:13:50,906
What are the economics
of their business?

00:13:50,906 --> 00:13:51,974
So far, so good.
Knock on wood.

00:13:51,974 --> 00:13:53,642
Are they profitable?
They are.

00:13:53,642 --> 00:13:56,879
What's the average bill
in the sit-Down restaurant?

00:13:56,879 --> 00:13:59,148
Roughly, it's around
$10 to $12.

00:13:59,148 --> 00:14:01,283
Sushi's good.
Let's talk money.
Yeah.

00:14:01,283 --> 00:14:03,285
You're offering me 12%
of the corporate entity...

00:14:03,285 --> 00:14:04,620
correct.

00:14:04,620 --> 00:14:05,621
That owns
all the franchise flows

00:14:05,621 --> 00:14:07,623
for $1 million.

00:14:07,623 --> 00:14:09,291
That is correct.

00:14:09,291 --> 00:14:10,759
So what is this year's
cash flow gonna look like?

00:14:10,759 --> 00:14:14,096
Just on royalties,
it's $250,000 a year.

00:14:14,096 --> 00:14:14,897
Wow.

00:14:17,432 --> 00:14:19,434
What are your sales
in the corporate stores?

00:14:19,434 --> 00:14:21,170
Oh, uh, one is running
600-something-thousand,

00:14:21,170 --> 00:14:24,039
and the other one
is running $400,000.

00:14:24,039 --> 00:14:24,907
(Barbara)
I would like to ask,

00:14:24,907 --> 00:14:27,309
I'm going to buy a franchise.

00:14:27,309 --> 00:14:29,278
Tell me
what I have to pay you.

00:14:29,278 --> 00:14:31,613
Okay. So the all-in cost
of the franchise,

00:14:31,613 --> 00:14:33,348
including the $20,000
in franchise fee,

00:14:33,348 --> 00:14:36,018
the building out of the store,
buying the equipment--

00:14:36,018 --> 00:14:39,154
$270,000, $300,000 all in.
Mm-hmm.

00:14:39,154 --> 00:14:40,489
(Daymond) So it looks like--
now they're in business.

00:14:40,489 --> 00:14:42,224
Yes.
But what happens after that?

00:14:42,224 --> 00:14:43,358
You get a percentage
of what they sell?

00:14:43,358 --> 00:14:44,760
That is correct.
A royalty.

00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:45,427
What's your royalty rate?

00:14:45,427 --> 00:14:46,762
Our royalty rate is 7%.

00:14:46,762 --> 00:14:48,363
What are the compliance systems
you have

00:14:48,363 --> 00:14:49,898
to make sure
you're getting paid?

00:14:49,898 --> 00:14:51,233
Uh, we suck it right out
of their checking account

00:14:51,233 --> 00:14:52,634
every week.

00:14:52,634 --> 00:14:53,569
(laughs)
So you mean, in other words,

00:14:53,569 --> 00:14:55,237
they have to set up
a corporate account...
that is correct.

00:14:55,237 --> 00:14:56,972
(Mark) Guys,
let me jump first.

00:14:56,972 --> 00:14:59,575
I-I like the idea.
I like the concept.

00:14:59,575 --> 00:15:02,144
But that's
a brutally competitive area.

00:15:02,144 --> 00:15:04,813
I don't want to be
in the sushi business,

00:15:04,813 --> 00:15:07,216
so I'm out.

00:15:11,086 --> 00:15:13,488
(Kevin) I-I'm looking at it
from a different perspective.

00:15:13,488 --> 00:15:15,157
I believe
it's very well managed.

00:15:15,157 --> 00:15:15,824
I think
your presentation's excellent.

00:15:15,824 --> 00:15:17,492
And you have
the right combination--

00:15:17,492 --> 00:15:19,228
The chef guy
with the finance guy.

00:15:19,228 --> 00:15:22,231
That's perfect.
The valuation is rich.

00:15:22,231 --> 00:15:23,232
It--It is probably
a little bit high.

00:15:23,232 --> 00:15:26,435
We--we have had a, uh,
letter of intent sent to us

00:15:26,435 --> 00:15:29,037
to, uh, buy 75%
of the company.

00:15:29,037 --> 00:15:30,639
And, uh, that valuation

00:15:30,639 --> 00:15:32,641
came in at 6.6.
Ah.

00:15:32,641 --> 00:15:34,533
Are you going
to do that deal?

00:15:34,533 --> 00:15:35,834
Uh, I-I don't think so.

00:15:35,834 --> 00:15:37,169
I don't think you should.

00:15:37,169 --> 00:15:38,837
Yeah, the reason why is,
because number one,

00:15:38,837 --> 00:15:40,973
I don't want to lose
that much of the company.

00:15:40,973 --> 00:15:42,975
Uh, really, honestly,
with the opening

00:15:42,975 --> 00:15:44,176
of, uh, four or five
more stores,

00:15:44,176 --> 00:15:46,645
our royalties will--will--
Will get us to--

00:15:46,645 --> 00:15:48,781
to profitability.
What's your geography right now?
Are they all in Texas?

00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:52,184
No. They are in, uh,
California, Marina Del Rey,

00:15:52,184 --> 00:15:53,519
uh, we have one
in Phoenix, Arizona,

00:15:53,519 --> 00:15:55,454
Tucson, Arizona.

00:15:55,454 --> 00:15:56,989
Yuen, I got--I gotta tell you,
man, you--You started a business

00:15:56,989 --> 00:15:57,656
a few years ago,

00:15:57,656 --> 00:16:01,927
and someone's offering you
$6.6 million in cash...

00:16:01,927 --> 00:16:03,529
Mm-hmm.
You'd be
a multimillionaire overnight,

00:16:03,529 --> 00:16:05,931
and you're just talking about
turning it down like that.

00:16:05,931 --> 00:16:06,598
We are.
Power to you,
'cause I gotta tell you,

00:16:06,598 --> 00:16:08,934
the first time somebody
offered me a million bucks...

00:16:08,934 --> 00:16:10,235
Yeah.

00:16:10,235 --> 00:16:11,570
I--it took me weeks
to say no.

00:16:11,570 --> 00:16:13,372
I understand.
I wanted to grab that check...

00:16:13,372 --> 00:16:15,307
right.
And run.

00:16:15,307 --> 00:16:15,908
(Yuen and Barbara laugh)

00:16:15,908 --> 00:16:18,644
(Daymond) So, guys, the profit
that you make in food

00:16:18,644 --> 00:16:21,246
is in appetizers,

00:16:21,246 --> 00:16:23,649
liquor and/or beverages,
and desserts.

00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:24,917
There's no money in this,

00:16:24,917 --> 00:16:26,986
and you're selling fish--
Fresh fish.

00:16:26,986 --> 00:16:28,654
I think that the margins
are gonna be too low.

00:16:28,654 --> 00:16:30,589
I'm out.

00:16:30,589 --> 00:16:32,324
Okay.

00:16:34,059 --> 00:16:35,394
Great presentation.

00:16:35,394 --> 00:16:37,329
Uh, more importantly,
great food.

00:16:37,329 --> 00:16:39,531
Um...

00:16:39,531 --> 00:16:40,799
I can't help you
with the operation.

00:16:40,799 --> 00:16:45,104
I don't understand
this particular food model.

00:16:45,104 --> 00:16:47,706
You're running
a great, great business.

00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:49,842
Thank you.

00:16:49,842 --> 00:16:50,509
I'll bring all my buddies,
we'll spend a lot of money...

00:16:50,509 --> 00:16:52,378
okay. Thank you.

00:16:52,378 --> 00:16:55,647
But we're not gonna spend
$1 million to invest today.

00:16:55,647 --> 00:16:57,850
I'm out.

00:16:57,850 --> 00:17:01,253
You have 15 locations
in 2 1/2 years.

00:17:01,253 --> 00:17:03,188
That is correct.
Amazing.

00:17:03,188 --> 00:17:03,522
Thank you.

00:17:03,522 --> 00:17:05,791
I have recently gotten involved

00:17:05,791 --> 00:17:07,126
in two different
food franchises,

00:17:07,126 --> 00:17:10,062
and I'm quickly learning
how complicated it is.

00:17:10,062 --> 00:17:11,397
It can be.

00:17:11,397 --> 00:17:13,332
So I have great respect
for where you came from

00:17:13,332 --> 00:17:13,932
and how far you got.

00:17:13,932 --> 00:17:15,601
Thank you.
But I mistrust it.

00:17:15,601 --> 00:17:16,902
I think your presentation
is so buttoned up...

00:17:16,902 --> 00:17:18,570
uh-huh.

00:17:18,570 --> 00:17:21,440
And for my liking,
a little too buttoned up.

00:17:21,440 --> 00:17:24,576
So I'm gonna trust my gut
on this. I'm out.

00:17:24,576 --> 00:17:26,578
Okay.

00:17:26,578 --> 00:17:27,646
Um...

00:17:27,646 --> 00:17:29,581
I like your business.
I like you guys.

00:17:29,581 --> 00:17:30,916
Thank you.

00:17:30,916 --> 00:17:33,585
So I'll make you
an offer.

00:17:33,585 --> 00:17:36,121
I'll give you $1 million.

00:17:36,121 --> 00:17:37,656
(Daymond) Whoa.

00:17:37,656 --> 00:17:39,124
Wow.

00:17:39,124 --> 00:17:42,394
But I want 22%
of the business.

00:17:46,665 --> 00:17:48,200
And there's one caveat.

00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:52,438
♪♪

00:17:56,942 --> 00:17:57,743
Four sharks are out,

00:17:57,743 --> 00:18:00,412
and Peter and Yuen
have an offer on the table.

00:18:00,412 --> 00:18:03,282
I'll give you $1 million.

00:18:03,282 --> 00:18:05,150
(Daymond) Whoa.

00:18:05,150 --> 00:18:07,286
Wow.

00:18:07,286 --> 00:18:09,955
But I want 22%
of the business.

00:18:09,955 --> 00:18:11,824
There's one caveat.

00:18:11,824 --> 00:18:14,760
I want a monthly distribution
prorated to the owners.

00:18:14,760 --> 00:18:18,831
In other words, the partners--
Obviously, you are the majors--

00:18:18,831 --> 00:18:22,901
We get a check every month
from the free cash

00:18:22,901 --> 00:18:24,136
that's coming from franchisees.

00:18:24,136 --> 00:18:27,606
Percentage
we can negotiate in the future.

00:18:27,606 --> 00:18:29,541
That's the only request
I have,

00:18:29,541 --> 00:18:32,344
and you get $1 million.

00:18:32,344 --> 00:18:35,347
So you're giving them a value
of $5 million on the business?

00:18:35,347 --> 00:18:36,748
Less than. Less than.
(Mark) Less than $5 million.

00:18:36,748 --> 00:18:38,083
(Robert) Right.
And on top of that,

00:18:38,083 --> 00:18:39,618
he's getting
a check every month...

00:18:39,618 --> 00:18:41,887
(Kevin) Well, guys,
I want to tell you something.
To reduce his equity.

00:18:41,887 --> 00:18:43,755
I bring a lot of value
to the table here.

00:18:43,755 --> 00:18:45,424
I know this space.
Okay.

00:18:45,424 --> 00:18:47,426
Not sushi rolling,
But franchise...
Mm-hmm.

00:18:47,426 --> 00:18:48,627
And the economics
of investing in this.

00:18:48,627 --> 00:18:50,896
I'll force
some disciplines on you

00:18:50,896 --> 00:18:52,030
that you'll thank me for
five years from now.

00:18:52,030 --> 00:18:53,499
Ha!

00:18:53,499 --> 00:18:55,033
Can you--Can you elaborate
a little bit about

00:18:55,033 --> 00:18:56,468
what disciplines you might
be alluding to?

00:18:56,468 --> 00:18:57,669
(sharks laugh)

00:18:57,669 --> 00:18:59,004
All I'm saying is,

00:18:59,004 --> 00:18:59,738
the only covenant
I'm putting in place is--

00:18:59,738 --> 00:19:02,074
is to make you
more money monthly.

00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:03,142
I'm going to sit down
with you and negotiate

00:19:03,142 --> 00:19:05,010
what portion
of the free cash flow

00:19:05,010 --> 00:19:07,679
that comes from
the royalty stream

00:19:07,679 --> 00:19:09,548
goes into your pocket
every month.
